tps://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-5-compulsory-measurements/"><meta itemprop="mainEntityOfPage" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-5-compulsory-measurements/"><meta itemprop="datePublished" content="2017-11-30T16:02:26+00:00"><meta itemprop="dateModified" content="2017-11-30T16:02:26+00:00"><meta itemprop="copyrightYear" content="2017"><meta itemprop="inLanguage" content="en_US"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tutorial 5. Compulsory Measurements."><meta itemprop="headline" content="Tutorial 5. Compulsory Measurements."><meta itemprop="description" content="I divide corset measurements in two categories: there are compulsory measurements and there are supplementary measurements"><meta itemprop="articleSection" content="Wedding and Evening Dresses. Theoretical Part."><meta itemprop="keywords" content="wedding and evening dresses. theoretical part., video"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><div itemprop="articleBody"><h1>Tutorial 5. Compulsory Measurements.</h1><p><strong>It is time to talk about taking measurements.</strong></p><p><strong>I divide corset measurements in two categories: </strong>there are <strong>compulsory measurements</strong> which must always be taken regardless of the style of the garment, and there are <strong>supplementary measurements </strong>which depend on the style of the garment and other custom features.</p><p><strong>Let us first talk about the compulsory measurements </strong>required to sew every non-see-through corset.</p><p><strong>I start by drawing all key measurement lines relevant for the given order on the female body drawing in the order form. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%205.files/image002.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>These key measurements are:</strong></p><p>- Bust Circumference,</p><p>- Bust Width Front,</p><p>- Under-Bust Circumference,</p><p>- Under-Bust Width Front,</p><p>- Waist Circumference,</p><p>- Stomach Circumference,</p><p>- Bust Princess Seam to Bust Princess Seam (aka Bust Princess Seam Width),</p><p>- Clip.</p><p>Hip Circumference is usually irrelevant for corsets.</p><p><strong>I measure all circumferences the traditional way and write each value next to the corresponding line marked on the order form. </strong></p><p><strong>Bust Circumference is 88cm.</strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%205.files/image004.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>Please remember</strong> to tighten the measuring tape when measuring the Bust Circumference on a woman in a push-up bra and to loosen it when working with a woman with full breasts in a minimizer bra.</p><p><strong>Under-Bust Circumference is 76cm.</strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%205.files/image006.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>Waist Circumference is 66cm. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%205.files/image008.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>You should keep the measuring tape tight for the Waist Circumference. </strong>In most cases, you can safely tighten it by 15-20mm. Of course, I cannot do this on a dress-form, but it is quite easy on a real person. If you do it this way, the corset will have a very nice snug fit and cling to the wearer’s body in a comfortable way. Wearing a corset that is not tight enough in the waist is really awkward. I bet you have seen it many times when a bride has to keep pulling up her dress by tugging at the top edge. This clearly indicates that the corset is looser than needed in the waist. If you remove 15-20mm from the Waist Circumference, your client will never notice it: she might even ask to make it tighter.</p><p><strong>Moreover, when you are taking and adjusting the Waist Circumference measurement, I highly recommend you should pay attention to fat deposits commonly found under your client’s rib cage close to the waistline. </strong></p><p><strong>If your client’s body is soft enough in this rib cage area, </strong>then you can safely remove a couple of centimeters from her Waist Circumference.</p><p><strong>But you should be very careful with waist restriction if your client’s ribs are palpable and protruding.</strong> In order words, if your client’s body has a pronounced slanted transition from the ribs to the waist, then the corset is likely to turn out way too narrow in the waist if you tighten it that much. It will squeeze the girl’s body making her feel not just plain discomfort but some kind of torture during her special day.</p><p><strong>I want to emphasize </strong>that you must always pay attention to all individual anatomic features of your client’s body when measuring her Waist Circumference and then adjusting the standard pattern to her measurements.</p><p><strong>My dress-form has a Waist Circumference of 68cm. I will make it 66cm. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%205.files/image010.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>Stomach Circumference is 88cm (11cm). </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%205.files/image012.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>Never tighten the measuring tape around your client’s stomach when taking her Stomach Circumference measurement! </strong>It should cling to the body without squeezing it. <strong>And you must always record the distance from the waistline at which this measurement was taken – 11cm in my case.</strong></p><p><strong>And now let me say what to do when you need some tummy control effect. </strong>If your client has a soft flabby stomach which can and should be shaped, then you should, first of all, decide on the shape of the bottom edge of the corset. If it is a downward facing “V,” then the stomach will only get shaped at the sides, i.e. at the level of the tied cord. There will be no tummy control effect in the area below the cord. And if the woman also has rather flabby sides, then the stomach will look flat in the straight part of the corset but there will be a very unpretty bulge in the middle of the “V.”</p><p><strong>Make sure to think over the shape of the bottom edge if you want to improve the shape of the stomach. </strong>When the corset has a V-shaped bottom edge, the bottom part of the outfit (i.e. skirt or trousers) must possess corresponding volume to disguise those bulging parts of the body. And when the garment has a more or less straight skirt, it makes sense to use a retro-style shape for the bottom edge of the corset: for example, make it longer at the sides with a smooth round wave in the middle of the front.</p><p><strong>There is a course at the Corset Academy called “Décor and Accessories Encyclopedia. Issue 2. Patchwork Corsets.” </strong>It includes a pattern of a corset which allows you to tighten the stomach and the hips.</p><p><strong>And now I want to focus on Bust Princess Seam Width. </strong>I talked about this measurement very many times but, judging from your E-mails, not everyone got this information so I must repeat it again.</p><p><strong>In more traditional garments, you measure the distance between bust apex points. </strong></p><p><strong>In corset garments, however, you measure the distance between bust princess seams. </strong>Bust princess seams at the front of the corset may not necessarily run through the bust apex points.</p><p><strong>The larger the bust is, the smaller the distance between the bust princess seams should be. </strong>This is how we make the bust look a little smaller. For a woman with a Bust Circumference of 110-115cm, for example, an average Bust Princess Seam Width will be 24-25cm. It is our duty to make the bust look beautiful, well-proportionate, and aesthetically pleasing! And this is why we purposely use a slightly smaller Bust Princess Seam Width when we want to make a full bust appear smaller, too. Instead of the average 25cm, we can make it, say, 23cm thereby putting the bust princess seams closer to each other and visually improving the proportions!</p><p><strong>Naturally, smaller breasts require larger distance between the bust princess seams. </strong>This means we will do the opposite thing and increase the average measurement to visually broaden the chest and make small breasts appear a little fuller. Girls with a Bust Circumference of 88-90cm, for example, have an average Bust Princess Seam Width of 17-18cm, and we should make it 20cm to increase the distance between the bust princess seams and make the bust appear larger.</p><p>I believe it is now clear that you can use the same corset pattern for several sizes just by changing the distance between the bust princess seams correspondingly. The lacing at the back also helps.</p><p><strong>I made this small digression to help you understand the role of this measurement (i.e. Bust Princess Seam Width) in corsets. </strong></p><p><strong>And now let us return to the process of measuring the distance between the bust princess seams. </strong></p><p><strong>My dress-form’s Bust Circumference is 88cm. </strong></p><p><strong>This corresponds with an average Bust Princess Seam Width of 17.5cm. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%205.files/image014.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>But I will make it 20cm because I want my client’s bust to look more graceful and proportionate. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%205.files/image016.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>Before making the final decision, I step away from the client, examine her from a distance, and make sure that I do want to slightly increase the distance between the bust princess seams. </strong></p><p>Now I can safely decide to make this distance 20cm for this particular woman.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%205.files/image018.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>I position the measuring tape symmetrically in the centre of the front, find the end of the previously measured Bust Princess Seam Width, and place my thumb at this point. </strong></p><p>You can mark this point with a pin to make it easier.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%205.files/image020.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>Clip measurements are taken from this very point, i.e. the end point of Bust Princess Seam Width. </strong></p><p><strong>Clip toward Armscye: </strong></p><p><strong>Keeping my thumb at the specified point, I feel my client’s underarm with my index finger to find the edge of that flabby area which tends to hang over the armscye of the corset. </strong></p><p>Every woman, regardless of her build, is familiar with this terrible underarm flab. It must be disguised!</p><p>You basically imitate the hard edge of the corset clinging to the woman’s underarm area.</p><p><strong>There is a very fine line here: </strong>you need to find the right level which will allow you to prevent fat overhang without the hard edge of the corset rubbing on your client’s skin and irritating the armpits.</p><p><strong>It is a highly important detail and you must eventually learn to sense it!</strong> Experience matters, of course, but I can assure you that it will grow easier and easier with each new order.</p><p><strong>After finding the required area, you take your measuring tape and measure the Clip toward Armscye. </strong>Unlike circumference measurements, clips require 100% accuracy! Every millimeter makes a difference.</p><p><strong>My Clip toward Armscye is 10cm. </strong>I mark it on the drawing in the order form.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%205.files/image022.jpg" alt=""></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%205.files/image024.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>Clip toward Top of Cup: </strong></p><p><strong>Suppose the front of your corset has a pointy corner at the top of the cup which gradually goes down to form a V-shaped low neckline. </strong></p><p>Looking at the client and keeping your thumb at the end point of Bust Princess Seam Width, you decide where to position this top pointy corner of the cup, i.e. the start point of the beautiful neckline curve.</p><p><strong>You place your index finger at this new point. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%205.files/image026.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>And you measure the resulting Clip toward Top of Cup and mark it on the drawing in the order form. Mine is 11.5cm. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%205.files/image028.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>I still need to measure a Clip toward Neckline. </strong></p><p><strong>This is another important measurement which determines how low you can make the neckline. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%205.files/image030.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>There is an objective law: the fuller your client’s bust is, the more you should cover up. And, vice versa: the smaller the bust, the more you should reveal. </strong></p><p><strong>This law has a perfectly logical explanation to it. </strong>It is clear that the size of cups depends on the distance from the middle of the breast to the neckline.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%205.files/image032.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>Fuller breasts require larger and deeper cups, which means the distance from the middle of the breast to the neckline should be increased. </strong></p><p>For this reason, you need to cover up a larger area of a full bust, and the more you cover up, the larger is the distance to the neckline and, consequently, the less open the neckline itself. Only in this case full breasts will look aesthetic and not vulgar in a corset.</p><p><strong>We normally use push-up pads when sewing a corset for a woman with small breasts. </strong>Push-up pads are used to push the breasts up and together to create the cleavage look. And the desired cleavage look requires shallow cups! If the cups are too large, the push-up pads will not be able to push the breasts up and together.</p><p><strong>Thus smaller breasts require smaller distance from the middle of the breast to the neckline so you can reveal more. </strong></p><p><strong>My dress-form has a Bust Circumference of 88cm. This means rather small breasts and, therefore, my Clip toward Neckline will also be small. </strong></p><p><strong>You place your index finger at the end point of Bust Princess Seam Width and measure the distance to the neckline in the cleavage area with your thumb.</strong> It will really help if you look at the position of the edge of your client’s bra. The shape of her bra allows you to imagine the desired neckline shape and see how her bust behaves with the existing push-up pads in the bra.</p><p><strong>&nbsp;If you see that your client’s bra meets all your requirements, then you can measure the Clip toward Neckline from the end point of Bust Princess Seam Width to the edge of the bra.</strong></p><p><strong>My Clip toward Neckline is 6cm. </strong>I mark it on the order form.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%205.files/image034.jpg" alt=""></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%205.files/image036.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>There are two more compulsory measurements which indicate the position of the side seam. </strong></p><p><strong>Bust Width Front – 46cm.</strong> It is the distance from side seam to side seam taken along the bust line.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%205.files/image038.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>Under-Bust Width Front – 39cm.</strong> It is the distance from side seam to side seam taken along the under-bust line.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%205.files/image040.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>All these measurements are compulsory! </strong>You won’t be able to sew a corset if you forget at least one of them! But it is hard to forget something when you have all these reference lines before your eyes on the order form.</p><p><strong>The drawing on the order form will look something like this: arrows and measurement values written next to them. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%205.files/image042.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>There are basically no compulsory measurements related to the back of the garment. </strong>And yet I do recommend you should always take one helpful measurement for it.</p><p><strong>Ask your client to stand up, bend her arms at the elbows, and move them back a little. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%205.files/image044.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>This position will help you easily find the bottom edge of her shoulder blades. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%205.files/image046.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>This bottom shoulder blade line is crucial for defining the right length for the back of the corset. </strong></p><p><strong>Please remember that the top edge of the back should go about 1cm below that shoulder blade line. </strong>If it goes right along the shoulder blade line, you will inevitably get that fat overhang regardless of your client’s build. A corset is a hard construction which sits tightly around the waist and cannot move vertically. If the top edge of its back is pushed in the shoulder blades, whenever your client stands in a beautiful pose with her shoulders open, her shoulder blades will naturally come close to each other and start poking out forming a bulge above the top edge of the corset. So I recommend you should keep it 1cm below the shoulder blade line if you want your client’s back to look graceful. If your garment is supposed to have a high back, then make sure the top edge goes above the shoulder blades.</p><p><strong>And this is why I recommend you take a Waist to Shoulder Blade measurement. </strong>I draw an upward vertical arrow on the drawing of the back and write the measurement next to it. <strong>Of course, I cannot measure it on a dress-form but my experience says it should be about 18cm for this body type. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%205.files/image048.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>All other measurements are supplementary and taken after you have a finished sketch of the garment. We will talk about them in the next tutorial. </strong></p></div> <!-- Itemprop END: articleBody --></div> <!-- Scope END: Article --><!-- END Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin --> 					</div>															<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="pattern">						<p>Sewing patterns are in PDF format.</p><p>To print sewing patterns open the files, press “print” and choose “<strong>PRINT IN ACTUAL SIZE</strong>“.</p><p>In each&nbsp;file the pattern is divided &nbsp;to A4 paper sheets for home printer.</p><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/patterns/4%20curves%20corset%20-%20boat.pdf" target="_blank" class=""><img src="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset-rs/img/pdf.png"> Boat-Neck Corset with 4 Princess Seams</a><br><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/patterns/4%20curves%20corset%20-%20strapless.pdf" target="_blank" class=""><img src="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset-rs/img/pdf.png"> Strapless Corset with 4 Princess Seams</a><br><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/patterns/4%20curves%20corset%20-%20V%20neck.pdf" target="_blank" class=""><img src="https://corsetacad